1

00:00:00,000  -->  00:00:04,580
Let's compare our model to some models created by OpenAI.

2

00:00:04,580  -->  00:00:09,395
The very first model released by OpenAI was called GPT-1.

3

00:00:09,395  -->  00:00:12,980
It had 120 million parameters,

4

00:00:12,980  -->  00:00:18,255
12 layers, and was trained on 4.5 gigabytes of data.

5

00:00:18,255  -->  00:00:24,460
Their next model called GPT-2 was a scaled up version of GPT-1.

6

00:00:24,460  -->  00:00:26,440
It has the same architecture,

7

00:00:26,440  -->  00:00:29,700
but had around 10 times more parameters,

8

00:00:29,700  -->  00:00:31,800
four times more layers,

9

00:00:31,800  -->  00:00:37,240
and they also used 10 times more training data to train this model.

10

00:00:37,240  -->  00:00:43,015
They then scaled up this architecture again and created the GPT-3 model,

11

00:00:43,015  -->  00:00:47,025
which becomes the foundation for their ChatGPT product.

12

00:00:47,025  -->  00:00:49,920
This model had even more layers,

13

00:00:49,920  -->  00:00:54,390
more parameters, and was strained on even more data.

14

00:00:54,390  -->  00:00:57,870
We don't know a lot about their most recent models,

15

00:00:57,870  -->  00:01:00,830
but it is rumored that it is based on

16

00:01:00,830  -->  00:01:05,490
a mixture of different models that have even more parameters.

17

00:01:05,490  -->  00:01:09,790
One trend that you can see is that the bigger the model is,

18

00:01:09,790  -->  00:01:12,430
the more capable it usually becomes,

19

00:01:12,430  -->  00:01:18,125
and there are already some models with one trillion parameters.

20

00:01:18,125  -->  00:01:22,150
Scaling models is not the only thing we need to do

21

00:01:22,150  -->  00:01:26,165
to achieve capabilities of products like ChatGPT.

22

00:01:26,165  -->  00:01:30,110
If we train a model that can simply predict next to word,

23

00:01:30,110  -->  00:01:33,170
it will only be able to generate text,

24

00:01:33,170  -->  00:01:38,085
but it won't be able to answer questions like ChatGPT.

25

00:01:38,085  -->  00:01:46,240
This doesn't depend on the amount of training data that we use or the model size.

26

00:01:46,240  -->  00:01:49,090
To give you an example of how this works,

27

00:01:49,090  -->  00:01:52,970
I've sent the following prompt to one of the older versions of

28

00:01:52,970  -->  00:01:58,490
GPT-3 that was trained to generate text instead of answering questions.

29

00:01:58,490  -->  00:02:01,290
As you can see, instead of answering a question,

30

00:02:01,290  -->  00:02:05,560
it started generating text related to the question.

31

00:02:05,560  -->  00:02:09,050
After being trained on a larger text corpus,

32

00:02:09,050  -->  00:02:12,010
it can only generate text that could be

33

00:02:12,010  -->  00:02:15,870
surrounding a text that looks like the provided prompt.

34

00:02:15,870  -->  00:02:19,815
In contrast, if you send this question to ChatGPT,

35

00:02:19,815  -->  00:02:25,865
it would return and answer like Paris and possibly provide some additional information.

36

00:02:25,865  -->  00:02:30,920
So how did OpenAI train the model that can answer questions?

37

00:02:30,920  -->  00:02:33,540
Let's take a high level overview.

38

00:02:33,540  -->  00:02:38,780
They first trained a GPT model which is similar to what we've built,

39

00:02:38,780  -->  00:02:42,195
but bigger and using much more data.

40

00:02:42,195  -->  00:02:46,875
Then they've used a data set of questions and answers.

41

00:02:46,875  -->  00:02:48,735
Having this data set,

42

00:02:48,735  -->  00:02:50,320
they updated weights of

43

00:02:50,320  -->  00:02:56,070
the trained GPT model to create a model that can answer questions.

44

00:02:56,070  -->  00:03:03,540
This new model that was produced as a result of this process was called GPT-3.5,

45

00:03:03,540  -->  00:03:07,685
and it was used by the first version of ChatGPT.

46

00:03:07,685  -->  00:03:12,720
This process of taking a model trained for one task and modifying

47

00:03:12,720  -->  00:03:17,755
its weights to work for a different task is called fine-tuning,

48

00:03:17,755  -->  00:03:20,540
and it is used not just for LOMs,

49

00:03:20,540  -->  00:03:24,120
but for other deep learning models as well.

50

00:03:24,120  -->  00:03:28,425
To fine-tune a model to perform question answering,

51

00:03:28,425  -->  00:03:31,200
OpenAI went through the following steps.

52

00:03:31,200  -->  00:03:36,820
First, they collected a dataset with different prompts and questions.

53

00:03:36,820  -->  00:03:40,880
Then they had humans answering questions and

54

00:03:40,880  -->  00:03:45,540
organized human provided answers into a data set.

55

00:03:45,540  -->  00:03:52,740
This data set was then used to fine-tune GPT-3 model to be trained to answer questions.

56

00:03:52,740  -->  00:03:56,680
After this, they went through a different process.

57

00:03:56,680  -->  00:04:00,660
Using prompts, they sampled several outputs from

58

00:04:00,660  -->  00:04:09,880
a model to generate multiple answers for the same question.

59

00:04:09,880  -->  00:04:13,910
Then people were ranking these answers against each other.

60

00:04:13,910  -->  00:04:15,875
Using these ranking results,

61

00:04:15,875  -->  00:04:19,005
OpenAI created another data set.

62

00:04:19,005  -->  00:04:23,720
This data set of ranked answers was used to train another model called

63

00:04:23,720  -->  00:04:28,820
the reward model that can calculate how good an answer to a prompt is.

64

00:04:28,820  -->  00:04:31,220
Finally, using the reward model,

65

00:04:31,220  -->  00:04:34,740
they fine-tuned GPT-3 model to give

66

00:04:34,740  -->  00:04:40,115
answers that are more closely aligned with the reward policy.

67

00:04:40,115  -->  00:04:46,170
As you can see, training a model that can answer questions is a complicated process.

68

00:04:46,170  -->  00:04:49,650
These datasets that were used for this are not

69

00:04:49,650  -->  00:04:54,210
shared by OpenAI and are much harder to collect.
